'''Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group: Mounded Tombs of Ancient Japan''' ({{lang|ja|百舌鳥・古市古墳群 -古代日本の墳墓群-}}) is a collective name for 45 kofun located in {{ill|Sakai|ja|堺市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Habikino|ja|羽曳野市|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Fujiidera|ja|藤井寺市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Osaka Prefecture, Japan. These tumuli are categorized into the {{ill|Mozu Kofun Group|ja|百舌鳥古墳群|1=Mozu Tombs|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Furuichi Kofun Group|ja|古市古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}}. The site was officially designated as a World Cultural Heritage Site during the {{ill|43rd World Heritage Committee|ja|第43回世界遺産委員会|12=draft|12=draft}} meeting on {{ill|July 6, 2019|ja|2019th year 7月6日|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20190706/k00/00m/040/180000c|title=Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group designated as World Heritage Site|publisher=Mainichi Shimbun|accessdate=2019-07-06}}</ref>
== Background and Preservation == === Nomination for World Heritage Listing === Efforts to nominate the Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group as a World Heritage Site began in 2007 when it was proposed to {{ill|Agency for Cultural Affairs (Japan)|ja|文化庁|12=draft|12=draft}}. After being included in Japan's tentative list in 2008, it was officially submitted to UNESCO in 2010.<ref>{{Cite book|title=World Heritage Yearbook 2009|publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs|date=2009}}</ref>
=== Preservation Measures === As many kofun are classified as {{ill|Imperial Mausoleum Reference Land|ja|陵墓参考地|1=Mausoleum Reference Site|12=draft|12=draft}} under the jurisdiction of the Imperial Household Agency, protection under the {{ill|Cultural Properties Protection Law|ja|文化財保護法|12=draft|12=draft}} is limited. Instead, preservation measures include restrictions on construction and landscape design under urban planning laws.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mozu-furuichi.jp/jp/conference/headquarters_nine_dl/gidai01.pdf|title=Preservation Measures for Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group|accessdate=2021-05-09}}</ref>
== Composition == The site comprises 45 kofun in three cities, dating from the late 4th to 5th centuries.
=== Notable Tumuli in the Mozu Area === * {{ill|Daisen Kofun|ja|大仙陵古墳|1=Daisenryō Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}: Japan's largest kofun, believed to be the tomb of {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Nagayama Kofun|ja|永山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}: Accompanying tumulus associated with the Daisen Kofun.
=== Notable Tumuli in the Furuichi Area === * {{ill|Konda Gobyo-yama Kofun|ja|誉田御廟山古墳|1=Konda Gobyoyama Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}: Believed to be the tomb of {{ill|Emperor Ojin|ja|応神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. * {{ill|Nakatsuyama Kofun|ja|仲津山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}: Attributed to {{ill|Nakatsuhime|lt=Empress Nakatsuhime|ja|仲姫命|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Related Information == * {{ill|Agency for Cultural Affairs (Japan)|ja|文化庁|12=draft|12=draft}} official page for Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group: [http://www.mozu-furuichi.jp/] * {{Cite book|title=Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group: Heritage and Preservation|author=Sakai City Cultural Property Division|year=2019}}
